comments.body:
@berndverst I've got an older topic in which I cover this in more detail, but I think there should be a rigorous second-generation rethink of how state is realized in Dapr and that there should be [specialized state store building blocks](#7339) instead of lumping it all under the current umbrella (and giving us a clean break from ideas like the current query capability that are effectively discontinued).

Under the guise of #7339 , this proposal is a rethink of what should minimally be offered through a second generation key/value store in Dapr in that it offers nearly what's available today, but also includes key-focused querying (which nearly every key/value store provider I've used supports), but which Dapr doesn't presently have any support for. So yes, I do want querying, but I want it optimized for key/value stores and I want it limited only to keys as that's what it expected in a key/value store.

Should a user want to be able to run queries against values, they can turn to the specialized API to query a Document Store or a Relational DB store or perhaps execute some sort of query against the metadata of the objects in an Object Store, but here, I propose that the building block be strictly an abstraction for Key/Value stores and have the limited querying (and other operations specific to key/value stores) to do with it.
